Ranking functions.

There are four ranking functions, all driven by the over, partition by, order by shape. They differ only in how they handle ties. Row number gives a strict one, two, three, and breaks ties arbitrarily. Rank gives one, two, two, four: ties share a rank, then a gap. Dense rank gives one, two, two, three: ties share a rank, with no gap. And n-tile of n splits the partition into n roughly equal buckets.

The classic use case is top n per group: rank within the partition, then keep ranks one through n. Modern dialects support the qualify clause for filtering on window-function results without wrapping in a subquery. Snowflake, BigQuery, DuckDB, and Databricks all support it; Postgres and sequel server require the subquery form.
